      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The transformation into new flavors is essentially a cascade of molecular restructuring. Initially, the sugars and amino acids react to form unstable intermediate compounds like Schiff bases. These intermediates then undergo complex fragmentation and cyclization reactions directly producing melanoidins (the color) and volatile molecules that our sense of smell interprets as \"roasted\" or \"nutty.\" Think of it as a precise, energetic chemical demolition and rebuilding process that yields a vast spectrum of flavor chemicals.",
      "source": "target",
