      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the temperature goes too high, the Maillard reaction will continue rapidly, leading to excessive carbonization, which tastes bitter and acrid. Conversely, if the moisture content is too high, the water molecules compete with the reactants, acting as a heat sink and slowing down the necessary dehydration steps. When moisture is too low initially, the reaction speeds up unevenly, sometimes promoting undesirable side reactions before the desired browning compounds fully develop.",
